This May, Christie=E2=80=99s will auction the $250 million collection of Le=
n Riggio,
the late founder of the bookstore chain Barnes & Noble. The first seven pie=
ces revealed from the collection=E2=80=94which is filled with historical wo=
rk=E2=80=94offer clues about the estimates and what the sale could mean for=
 the broader market.

Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Marion Maneker ( https://puck.news/author/marion-maneker/?utm_campaign=3DWa=
ll+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

At this stage in the art market cycle=E2=80=94after all the emerging talent=
 fads and
the downturn=E2=80=94we should probably be witnessing a new level of intere=
st in high-quality historical work. And now Christie=E2=80=99s, which won t=
he competition to auction some of Barnes & Noble founder Len Riggio=E2=80=
=99s art collection, will have a chance to test this proposition. More spec=
ifically, the auction house will attempt to sell the late entrepreneur=E2=
=80=99s $250 million collection of 30 works in their own dedicated evening =
sale in May.

=C2=A0

The works chosen for auction reflect a level of market confidence, and they=
 look like they were selected to raise the greatest amount of money while r=
emoving the fewest artworks from the collection. (The estate has to pay tax=
es, and this is probably the most convenient way to raise the money. Which =
would you rather sell right now: your investments or your art?) Christie=E2=
=80=99s hasn=E2=80=99t commented on whether the collection is directly guar=
anteed, but the estate may
have chosen to receive a larger portion of the total price paid in lieu of =
a guarantee. It=E2=80=99s also a bit early in the process for Christie=E2=
=80=99s to have put estimates on the works. (They may also be out there gat=
hering third-party guarantees before they publish the estimates closer to t=
he sale=E2=80=A6) Nevertheless, I=E2=80=99m going to give you my best educa=
ted guesses.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Christie=E2=80=99s is touring seven of the 30 works on
offer, all made in the 20th century and generally not the kind of art that =
most people associate with Riggio, who sat on the board of the Dia Art Foun=
dation. They include two paintings by Ren=C3=A9 Magritte and two sculptures=
 by Alberto Giacometti, as well as paintings by Pablo Picasso, Andy Warhol,=
 and Piet Mondrian. From the photograph of the Riggios=E2=80=99 Manhattan a=
partment in the promotional
materials, we know the sale will include a Balthus painting from 1944-45, a=
bout which Christie=E2=80=99s isn=E2=80=99t providing information just yet.

=C2=A0

The rest of the works are being kept under wraps until closer to the sale, =
but the selection suggests the Riggio estate is being strategic and market-=
minded. After all, the seven announced lots (and even the Balthus) respond =
to demand recently seen in the auction market.

Mondrian & Two Magrittes
------------------------

Composition with Large Red Plane, Bluish Gray, Yellow, Black and Blue, from
1922, will be the third square Mondrian with a dominant red rectangle to co=
me to market in the past decade. Only 21 inches, this work is actually slig=
htly larger than the two later works (from 1929 and 1930) that sold prior. =
And its provenance is likely to attract buyers: It was originally bought by=
 Antony Kok, a close friend of artist, before coming to the United States w=
ith Nelly van Doesburg, who sold it to Henri-Georges Doll, an executive at
Schlumberger and husband to heiress Anne Schlumberger, whose sister was the=
 collector Dominique de Menil. Doll owned the painting for 40 years=E2=80=
=94far longer than his marriage to Schlumberger.

Piet Mondrian,=C2=A0Composition with Large Red Plane, Bluish Gray, Yellow, =
Black and Blue=C2=A0(1922).=C2=A0Photo: Courtesy of Christie's

Piet Mondrian,=C2=A0Composition with Large Red Plane, Bluish Gray, Yellow, =
Black and
Blue=C2=A0(1922).

The Riggios bought their painting 25 years ago. In 2015, the 1929 work sold=
 at
auction for just above $50 million to the bond fund manager and museum patr=
on Jeffrey Gundlach. Six years later, a rectangular work from 1927 with a r=
ed section sold for $26 million. Then, in November of 2022, Composition II,=
 a 1930 work that is very similar in appearance to the Riggios=E2=80=99 pai=
nting, sold for $51 million.

=C2=A0

With that in mind, Christie=E2=80=99s is likely to estimate the work
close to the record price. They=E2=80=99ll be setting a bar, and we=E2=80=
=99ll be watching to see whether that rarefied world of a few dozen collect=
ors thinks it=E2=80=99s a reasonable price=E2=80=94or even cheap. Adding to=
 the appeal of the Riggios=E2=80=99 Mondrian is the fact that the painting =
seems to be in very good condition=E2=80=94often an issue for Mondrian=E2=
=80=99s work a century after he made it.

Close behind the Mondrian is one of the Magrittes that the Riggios acquired=
 only in 2023. A small version of
L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res, from 1949, this painting had been sold =
in 2017 for $20.5 million. It returned to auction amid the run-up in Magrit=
te prices, and contributed to steep acceleration in prices for this particu=
lar series when the Riggios bought it for nearly $35 million.

Ren=C3=A9 Magritte, L=E2=80=99empire des lumier=C3=A8s (1949). Photo: Court=
esy of Christie's

Ren=C3=A9 Magritte, L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res (1949).

Normally, selling a recently purchased painting so quickly would be difficu=
lt.
But, as everyone knows, the top price for a Magritte rose from $79 million =
in 2022 to $121 million in 2024=E2=80=94and both of those sales were for wo=
rks from the L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res series. A gouache from the =
series set a huge new record late last year at nearly $19 million. Does tha=
t mean this painting will sell for 50 percent more than it did in 2023? In =
any case, the estimate was $25 million when the Riggios bought it. Maybe th=
is time it will carry a slightly higher one=E2=80=94$30 million or
even $35 million.

The other Magritte, Les droits de l=E2=80=99homme, from 1947-48, also has a=
n interesting provenance=E2=80=94and, with the recent show celebrating the =
100th anniversary of Andr=C3=A9 Breton=E2=80=99s Surrealist Manifesto held =
at the Centre Pompidou, there are now likely more potential buyers for this=
 work than ever. This Magritte passed through dealer Alexander Iolas and, t=
wice, Pace Gallery. It was owned for a decade by
television game show producer and noted collector Mark Goodson. The paintin=
g is large: nearly 5 feet tall and 4 feet wide.

Ren=C3=A9 Magritte, Les droits de l=E2=80=99homme (1947-48). Photo: Courtes=
y of Christie's

Ren=C3=A9 Magritte, Les droits de l=E2=80=99homme (1947-48).

There are few comparable auction sales for the work; its size makes it a st=
andout. Smaller works
featuring a similar image but lacking this one=E2=80=99s flaming musical in=
strument have sold for $3 million and $2.4 million. And a tiny painting of =
the flaming brass instrument, itself, sold for $3.5 million in 2021. That m=
ight offer a clue about where this work will ultimately be estimated. Combi=
ning the two images with its size should get the estimate closer to $15 mil=
lion or $20 million, given the stamina of the Magritte market.

Relief for the Picasso Drought
------------------------------

Longtime readers will remember that the Picasso auction market basically sh=
ut
down last year, with a mere $167 million in sales, after averaging around $=
508 million each of the three previous years. This isn=E2=80=99t the first =
time that the Picasso market has gone dormant. According to ARTDAI=E2=80=99=
s numbers ( https://artd.ai/puck-news/?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIB=
ERS+%282%2F25%2F25%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F25%2F25=
%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617d=
a42abd12a ), there were similar volume drops in 2016, 2019, and 2020. Still=
, the demand for Picasso doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be flagging=E2=80=94it=E2=
=80=99s most likely a supply issue. Help may be on the way, starting with o=
ne
of the seven paintings that Picasso made of Lee Miller, the model and war p=
hotographer, and the subject of a 2023 film starring Kate Winslet. Miller w=
as a friend of Picasso, dating back to the 1930s through her own collaborat=
ions with Man Ray.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Femme =C3=A0 la coiffe d=E2=80=99Arl=C3=A9sienne sur fond vert (Lee Miller)=
, from 1937, follows two other versions
that were sold at Christie=E2=80=99s in recent years: In 2022, L=E2=80=99Ar=
l=C3=A9sienne (Lee Miller) sold for $13 million. In 2023, a more complex ve=
rsion painted 10 days later made almost twice that: $24.5 million. The one =
from the Riggio collection, made a day after the $13 million painting, is s=
lightly more complex than the first work, but not quite as developed as the=
 later one. It is likely to be estimated at $15 million or $20 million.

=C2=A0

Another work in the Riggio collection that was previously owned by Iolas is=
 Andy Warhol=E2=80=99s blue The Last Supper, made in 1986. The Riggios boug=
ht the painting at auction in 2010 for $6.8 million. Similar 40-by-40-inch =
Last Suppers, with two stacked reproductions of Leonardo=E2=80=99s famous f=
resco, have sold for much higher prices. The magenta version, for instance,=
 sold for nearly $19 million in 2017. A yellow one
sold for $8.2 million in 2018. Last year, a pink-and-red camouflage version=
 sold for $6 million. Good marketing suggests the Warhol will carry an esti=
mate closer to that last sale, with the potential for bidders to push it hi=
gher.

=C2=A0

The final two works announced for the sale are Giacometti sculptures cast i=
n 1958. One is the 41-inch version of the artist=E2=80=99s famous Femme de =
Venise I conceived in 1956.
There are six casts in the edition. This one passed through the prestigious=
 hands of Aim=C3=A9 Maeght, Claude Bernard, Pace Gallery, and Jeffrey Loria=
=2E Another sold at auction in 2007=20=
for $8 million=E2=80=94the same sale at w=
hich a different Giacometti work set a then-record price of $18 million.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

Since that time, Giacometti prices have exploded, with the record
set at $141 million in 2015. The next highest price for a Giacometti at auc=
tion was the $78 million that cryptocurrency billionaire Justin Sun paid fo=
r Harry and Linda Macklowe=E2=80=99s Le Nez, which has since been sold to D=
avid Geffen. (Sun recently sued Geffen, claiming the work was sold by his a=
rt advisor without his consent.) A cast of Femme de Venise III sold at Chri=
stie=E2=80=99s two years ago for $25 million.
Considering all that, the likely estimate for this work is probably a conse=
rvative $15 million.=C2=A0

The other Giacometti, while also cast in 1958, was conceived in 1927. Le Co=
uple is only 23 inches tall and was owned by the Museum of Modern Art for m=
ore than 25 years, before it was sold to Pace Gallery, who then sold it to =
the Riggios. In 2019, another cast was auctioned for $2.5 million. I=E2=80=
=99d expect Christie=E2=80=99s to estimate this one at $2-3 million.

