50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">At this stage in the art market cycle=E2=80=94after all the =
emerging talent fads and
the downturn=E2=80=94we should probably be witnessing a new level of intere=
st in high-quality historical work. And now Christie=E2=80=99s, which won t=
he competition to auction some of Barnes &amp; Noble founder <strong>Len Ri=
ggio</strong>=E2=80=99s art collection, will have a chance to test this pro=
position. More specifically, the auction house will attempt to sell the lat=
e entrepreneur=E2=80=99s $250 million collection of 30 works in their own d=
edicated evening sale in May.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The works chosen for auc=
tion reflect a level of market confidence, and they look like they were sel=
ected to raise the greatest amount of money while removing the fewest artwo=
rks from the collection. (The estate has to pay taxes, and this is probably=
 the most convenient way to raise the money. Which would you rather sell ri=
ght now: your investments or your art?) Christie=E2=80=99s hasn=E2=80=99t c=
ommented on whether the collection is directly guaranteed, but the estate m=
ay
have chosen to receive a larger portion of the total price paid in lieu of =
a guarantee. It=E2=80=99s also a bit early in the process for Christie=E2=
=80=99s to have put estimates on the works. (They may also be out there gat=
hering third-party guarantees before they publish the estimates closer to t=
he sale=E2=80=A6) Nevertheless, I=E2=80=99m going to give you my best educa=
ted guesses.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Christie=E2=80=99s is touring seven =
of the 30 works on
offer, all made in the 20th century and generally not the kind of art that =
most people associate with Riggio, who sat on the board of the Dia Art Foun=
dation. They include two paintings by <strong>Ren=C3=A9 Magritte</strong> a=
nd two sculptures by <strong>Alberto Giacometti</strong>, as well as painti=
ngs by <strong>Pablo Picasso</strong>, <strong>Andy Warhol</strong>, and <s=
trong>Piet Mondrian</strong>. From the photograph of the Riggios=E2=80=99 M=
anhattan apartment in the promotional
materials, we know the sale will include a <strong>Balthus</strong> paintin=
g from 1944-45, about which Christie=E2=80=99s isn=E2=80=99t providing info=
rmation just yet.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin:0;">The rest of the works are being kept under wraps until =
closer to the sale, but the selection suggests the Riggio estate is being s=
trategic and market-minded. After all, the seven announced lots (and even t=
he Balthus) respond to demand recently seen in the auction market.</p>
