<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"=
><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39=
;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:1=
50%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">Longtime readers will remember that the Picasso auction mark=
et basically shut
down last year, with a mere $167 million in sales, after averaging around $=
508 million each of the three previous years. This isn=E2=80=99t the first =
time that the Picasso market has gone dormant. According to ARTDAI=E2=80=99=
s <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uk=
txclJLZ0dWUDhWS1hZR3VvY25Ka0lZNlE0bz0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9hcnRkLmFpL3B1Y=
2stbmV3cy8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgyJTJGMjUl=
MkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVdhbGwrUG93ZXIrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjgyJTJ=
GMjUlMkYyNSUyOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT=
1jdXN0b21lci5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsI=
joiZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MjA2MzQ5Mn0/3a56f6eb0cee0ed8368a=
2c56fda39d9e560b8c383da7a2c84a2ad1b26aab9802" style=3D"text-decoration:unde=
rline;color:#d40000;">numbers</a>, there were similar volume drops in 2016,=
 2019, and 2020. Still, the demand for Picasso doesn=E2=80=99t seem to be f=
lagging=E2=80=94it=E2=80=99s most likely a supply issue. Help may be on the=
 way, starting with one
of the seven paintings that Picasso made of <strong>Lee Miller</strong>, th=
e model and war photographer, and the subject of a 2023 film starring <stro=
ng>Kate Winslet</strong>. Miller was a friend of Picasso, dating back to th=
e 1930s through her own collaborations with <strong>Man Ray</strong>.=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Femme =C3=A0 la coiffe d=E2=80=99Arl=C3=A9sienne s=
ur fond vert (Lee Miller)</em>, from 1937, follows two other versions
that were sold at Christie=E2=80=99s in recent years: In 2022, <em>L=E2=80=
=99Arl=C3=A9sienne (Lee Miller) </em>sold for $13 million. In 2023, a more =
complex version painted 10 days later made almost twice that: $24.5 million=
=2E The one from the Riggio collection,=
 made a day after the $13 million pain=
ting, is slightly more complex than the first work, but not quite as develo=
ped as the later one. It is likely to be estimated at $15 million or $20 mi=
llion.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Another work in the Riggio collection that was p=
reviously owned by Iolas is <strong>Andy Warhol</strong>=E2=80=99s blue <em=
>The Last Supper</em>, made in 1986. The Riggios bought the painting at auc=
tion in 2010 for $6.8 million. Similar 40-by-40-inch <em>Last Suppers</em>,=
 with two stacked reproductions of <strong>Leonardo</strong>=E2=80=99s famo=
us fresco, have sold for much higher prices. The magenta version, for insta=
nce, sold for nearly $19 million in 2017. A yellow one
sold for $8.2 million in 2018. Last year, a pink-and-red camouflage version=
 sold for $6 million. Good marketing suggests the Warhol will carry an esti=
mate closer to that last sale, with the potential for bidders to push it hi=
gher.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The final two works announced for the sale are Gi=
acometti sculptures cast in 1958. One is the 41-inch version of the artist=
=E2=80=99s famous <em>Femme de Venise I </em>conceived in 1956.
There are six casts in the edition. This one passed through the prestigious=
 hands of <strong>Aim=C3=A9 Maeght</strong>, <strong>Claude Bernard</strong=
>, Pace Gallery, and <strong>Jeffrey Loria</strong>. Another sold at auctio=
n in 2007 for $8 million=E2=80=94the same sale at which a different Giacome=
tti work set a then-record price of $18 million.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
Since that time, Giacometti prices have exploded, with the record
set at $141 million in 2015. The next highest price for a Giacometti at auc=
tion was the $78 million that cryptocurrency billionaire <strong>Justin Sun=
</strong> paid for <strong>Harry</strong> and <strong>Linda Macklowe</stron=
g>=E2=80=99s <em>Le Nez</em>, which has since been sold to <strong>David Ge=
ffen</strong>. (Sun recently sued Geffen, claiming the work was sold by his=
 art advisor without his consent.) A cast of <em>Femme de Venise III </em>s=
old at Christie=E2=80=99s two years ago for $25 million.
Considering all that, the likely estimate for this work is probably a conse=
rvative $15 million.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>The other Giacome=
tti, while also cast in 1958, was conceived in 1927. <em>Le Couple </em>is =
only 23 inches tall and was owned by the Museum of Modern Art for more than=
 25 years, before it was sold to Pace Gallery, who then sold it to the Rigg=
ios. In 2019, another cast was auctioned for $2.5 million. I=E2=80=99d expe=
ct Christie=E2=80=99s to estimate this one at $2-3 million.</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
